# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ldo-regulator
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] A **voltage regulator** is a system designed to automatically maintain a constant voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] It may use a simple feed-forward design or may include negative feedback.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] It may use an electromechanical mechanism or electronic components.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Depending on the design, it may be used to regulate one or more AC or DC voltages.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Electronic voltage regulators are found in devices such as computer power supplies, where they stabilize the DC voltages used by the processor and other elements.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] In automobile alternators and central power station generator plants, voltage regulators control the output of the plant.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] In an electric power distribution system, voltage regulators may be installed at a substation or along distribution lines so that all customers receive steady voltage independent of how much power is drawn from the line.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] A simple voltage regulator can be made from a resistor in series with a forward-biased diode (or series of diodes), forming a voltage divider of sorts.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Due to the logarithmic shape of diode V-I curves, the voltage across the diode changes only slightly due to changes in current drawn or changes in the input.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] When precise voltage control and efficiency are not important, this design may be adequate.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Since the forward voltage of a diode is small, this kind of voltage regulator is only suitable for low-voltage regulated output.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] When higher-voltage output is needed, a reverse-biased zener diode or a series of zener diodes may be employed.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Zener diode regulators make use of the zener diode's fixed reverse voltage, which can be quite large.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Feedback voltage regulators operate by comparing the actual output voltage to some fixed reference voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Any difference is amplified and used to control the regulation element in such a way as to reduce the voltage error.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] This forms a negative feedback control loop; increasing the open-loop gain tends to increase regulation accuracy but reduce stability.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Stability is the avoidance of oscillation, or ringing, during step changes in load or input voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] There will also be a trade-off between stability and the speed of the response to changes.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] However, many regulators have over-current protection, so that they will entirely stop sourcing current (or limit the current in some way) if the output current is too high, and some regulators may also shut down if the input voltage is outside a given range (see also: Crowbar (circuit)).
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] In electromechanical regulators, voltage regulation is easily accomplished by coiling the sensing wire to make an electromagnet.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The magnetic field produced by the current attracts a moving ferrous core held back under spring tension or gravitational pull.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] As voltage increases, so does the current, strengthening the magnetic field produced by the coil and pulling the core towards the field.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The magnet is physically connected to a mechanical power switch, which opens as the magnet moves into the field.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] As voltage decreases, so does the current, releasing spring tension or the weight of the core and causing it to retract.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] This closes the switch and allows the power to flow once more.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The relay(s) modulated the width of a current pulse to regulate the voltage output of the generator by controlling the average field current in the rotating machine which determines strength of the magnetic field produced which determines the unloaded output voltage per rpm.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Capacitors are not used to smooth the pulsed voltage as described earlier.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The large inductance of the field coil stores the energy delivered to the magnetic field in an iron core so the pulsed field current does not result in as strongly pulsed a field.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Both types of rotating machine produce a rotating magnetic field that induces an alternating current in the coils in the stator.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] A generator uses a mechanical commutator, graphite brushes running on copper segments, to convert the AC produced into DC by switching the external connections at the shaft angle when the voltage would reverse.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] An alternator accomplishes the same goal using rectifiers that do not wear down and require replacement.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Modern designs now use *solid state* technology (transistors) to perform the same function that the relays perform in electromechanical regulators.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Electromechanical regulators are used for mains voltage stabilisation—see AC voltage stabilizers below.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Generators, as used in power stations, ship electrical power production, or standby power systems, will have automatic voltage regulators (AVR) to stabilize their voltages as the load on the generators changes.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The first AVRs for generators were electromechanical systems, but a modern AVR uses solid-state devices.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] An AVR is a feedback control system that measures the output voltage of the generator, compares that output to a set point, and generates an error signal that is used to adjust the excitation of the generator.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] As the excitation current in the field winding of the generator increases, its terminal voltage will increase.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The AVR will control current by using power electronic devices; generally a small part of the generator's output is used to provide current for the field winding.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Where a generator is connected in parallel with other sources such as an electrical transmission grid, changing the excitation has more of an effect on the reactive power produced by the generator than on its terminal voltage, which is mostly set by the connected power system.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Where multiple generators are connected in parallel, the AVR system will have circuits to ensure all generators operate at the same power factor.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] AVRs on grid-connected power station generators may have additional control features to help stabilize the electrical grid against upsets due to sudden load loss or faults.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] This is an older type of regulator used in the 1920s that uses the principle of a fixed-position field coil and a second field coil that can be rotated on an axis in parallel with the fixed coil, similar to a variocoupler.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] When the movable coil is positioned perpendicular to the fixed coil, the magnetic forces acting on the movable coil balance each other out and voltage output is unchanged.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Rotating the coil in one direction or the other away from the center position will increase or decrease voltage in the secondary movable coil.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] This type of regulator can be automated via a servo control mechanism to advance the movable coil position in order to provide voltage increase or decrease.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] A braking mechanism or high-ratio gearing is used to hold the rotating coil in place against the powerful magnetic forces acting on the moving coil.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Electromechanical regulators called *voltage stabilizers* or *tap-changers*, have also been used to regulate the voltage on AC power distribution lines.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] These regulators operate by using a servomechanism to select the appropriate tap on an autotransformer with multiple taps, or by moving the wiper on a continuously variable auto transfomer.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] If the output voltage is not in the acceptable range, the servomechanism switches the tap, changing the turns ratio of the transformer, to move the secondary voltage into the acceptable region.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The controls provide a dead band wherein the controller will not act, preventing the controller from constantly adjusting the voltage ("hunting") as it varies by an acceptably small amount.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The **ferroresonant transformer**, **ferroresonant regulator** or **constant-voltage transformer** is a type of saturating transformer used as a voltage regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] These transformers use a tank circuit composed of a high-voltage resonant winding and a capacitor to produce a nearly constant average output voltage with a varying input current or varying load.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The circuit has a primary on one side of a magnet shunt and the tuned circuit coil and secondary on the other side.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Voltage regulation results from magnetic saturation in the portion of the core associated with the resonant winding and secondary.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The ferroresonant approach is attractive due to its lack of active components, relying on the square-loop magnetic characteristics of the core operating in saturation to absorb variations in average input voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Saturating transformers provide a simple rugged method to stabilize an AC power supply.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Older designs produced outputs with significant harmonic content.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Modern designs improve waveform quality, but the output is not an ideal sine wave.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The ferroresonant action is a flux limiter rather than a voltage regulator, but with a fixed supply frequency it can maintain an almost constant average output voltage even as the input voltage varies widely.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The ferroresonant transformers, which are also known as *constant-voltage transformers* (CVTs) or "ferros", are also good surge suppressors, as they provide high isolation and inherent short-circuit protection.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] A ferroresonant transformer can operate with an input voltage range ±40% or more of the nominal voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Output power factor remains in the range of 0.96 or higher from half to full load.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Because it regenerates an output voltage waveform, output distortion, which is typically less than 4%, is independent of any input voltage distortion, including notching.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Efficiency at full load is typically in the range of 89% to 93%.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] However, at low loads, efficiency can drop below 60%.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The current-limiting capability also becomes a handicap when a CVT is used in an application with moderate to high inrush current, like motors, transformers or magnets.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] In this case, the CVT has to be sized to accommodate the peak current, thus forcing it to run at low loads and poor efficiency.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Minimum maintenance is required, as transformers and capacitors can be very reliable.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Some units have included redundant capacitors to allow several capacitors to fail between inspections without any noticeable effect on the device's performance.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Output voltage varies about 1.2% for every 1% change in supply frequency.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] For example, a 2 Hz change in generator frequency, which is very large, results in an output voltage change of only 4%, which has little effect for most loads.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] It accepts 100% single-phase switch-mode power-supply loading without any requirement for derating, including all neutral components.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Input current distortion remains less than 8% THD even when supplying nonlinear loads with more than 100% current THD.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Drawbacks of CVTs are their larger size, audible humming sound, and the high heat generation caused by saturation.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Some ferroresonant transformer have active control.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Voltage regulators or stabilizers are used to compensate for voltage fluctuations in mains power.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Large regulators may be permanently installed on distribution lines.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Small portable regulators may be plugged in between sensitive equipment and a wall outlet.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Automatic voltage regulators on generator sets to maintain a constant voltage for changes in load.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The voltage regulator compensates for the change in load.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Power distribution voltage regulators normally operate on a range of voltages, for example 150–240 V or 90–280 V.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Many simple DC power supplies regulate the voltage using either series or shunt regulators, but most apply a voltage reference using a *shunt regulator* such as a Zener diode, avalanche breakdown diode, or voltage regulator tube.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The power supply is designed to only supply a maximum amount of current that is within the safe operating capability of the shunt regulating device.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] If the stabilizer must provide more power, the shunt output is only used to provide the standard voltage reference for the electronic device, known as the voltage stabilizer.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The voltage stabilizer is the electronic device, able to deliver much larger currents on demand.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Active regulators employ at least one active (amplifying) component such as a transistor or operational amplifier.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Shunt regulators are often (but not always) passive and simple, but always inefficient because they (essentially) dump the excess current which is not available to the load.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] When more power must be supplied, more sophisticated circuits are used.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] In the past, one or more vacuum tubes were commonly used as the variable resistance.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Modern designs like Shakti Servo use one or more transistors instead, perhaps within an integrated circuit.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Linear designs have the advantage of very "clean" output with little noise introduced into their DC output, but are most often much less efficient and unable to step-up or invert the input voltage like switched supplies.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] All linear regulators require a higher input than the output.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] If the input voltage approaches the desired output voltage, the regulator will "drop out".
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The input to output voltage differential at which this occurs is known as the regulator's drop-out voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Low-dropout regulators (LDOs) allow an input voltage that can be much lower (i.e., they waste less energy than conventional linear regulators).
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Entire linear regulators are available as integrated circuits.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] These chips come in either fixed or adjustable voltage types.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] A switching regulator works similar to an appliance charger.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] When battery charge is low, a charger is plugged in and energy is transferred to the battery.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] When charge is high, the charger disables itself, or is unplugged.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] A switching regulator nominally cycles hundreds to tens of thousands times per second automatically.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The duty cycle is controlled by a similar feedback mechanism as in a linear regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Because the series element is either fully conducting, or switched off, it dissipates almost no power; this is what gives the switching design its efficiency.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Switching regulators are also able to generate output voltages which are higher than the input, or of opposite polarity—something not possible with a linear design.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] In switched regulators, the pass transistor is used as a "controlled switch" and is operated at either cutoff or saturated state.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Hence the power transmitted across the pass device is in discrete pulses rather than a steady current flow.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Greater efficiency is achieved since the pass device is operated as a low-impedance switch.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] When the pass device is at cutoff, there is no current and it dissipates no power.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Again when the pass device is in saturation, a negligible voltage drop appears across it and thus dissipates only a small amount of average power, providing maximum current to the load.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] In either case, the power wasted in the pass device is very little and almost all the power is transmitted to the load.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Thus the efficiency of a switched-mode power supply is remarkably high – in the range of 70–90%.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Switched mode regulators rely on pulse-width modulation to control the average value of the output voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The average value of a repetitive-pulse waveform depends on the area under the waveform.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] When the duty cycle is varied, the average voltage changes proportionally.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Like linear regulators, nearly complete switching regulators are also available as integrated circuits (e.g.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Unlike linear regulators, these usually require an inductor for step-up or capacitor for step-down, that acts as the energy storage element.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The IC regulators combine the reference voltage source, error op-amp, and pass transistor with short-circuit current limiting and thermal-overload protection.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Switching regulators are more prone to input noise, output noise, and instability than linear regulators.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] However, they provide much better power efficiency than linear regulators.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Regulators powered from AC power circuits can use silicon controlled rectifiers (SCRs) as the series device.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Whenever the output voltage is below the desired value, the SCR is triggered, allowing electricity to flow into the load until the AC mains voltage passes through zero (ending the half cycle).
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] SCR regulators have the advantages of being both very efficient and very simple, but because they can not terminate an ongoing half cycle of conduction, they are not capable of very accurate voltage regulation in response to rapidly changing loads.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] An alternative is the SCR shunt regulator which uses the regulator output as a trigger.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Both series and shunt designs are noisy, but powerful, as the device has a low on resistance.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Many power supplies use more than one regulating method in series.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] For example, the output from a switching regulator can be further regulated by a linear regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The switching regulator accepts a wide range of input voltages and efficiently generates a (somewhat noisy) voltage slightly above the ultimately desired output.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] That is followed by a linear regulator that generates exactly the desired voltage and eliminates nearly all the noise generated by the switching regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Other designs may use an SCR regulator as the "pre-regulator", followed by another type of regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] An efficient way of creating a variable-voltage, accurate output power supply is to combine a multi-tapped transformer with an adjustable linear post-regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] A simple transistor regulator will provide a relatively constant output voltage *U*out for changes in the voltage *U*in of the power source and for changes in load *R*L, provided that *U*in exceeds *U*out by a sufficient margin and that the power handling capacity of the transistor is not exceeded.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The output voltage of the stabilizer is equal to the Zener diode voltage minus the base–emitter voltage of the transistor, *U*Z − *U*BE, where *U*BE is usually about 0.7 V for a silicon transistor, depending on the load current.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] In this case, the operational amplifier drives the transistor with more current if the voltage at its inverting input drops below the output of the voltage reference at the non-inverting input.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] Using the voltage divider (R1, R2 and R3) allows choice of the arbitrary output voltage between Uz and Uin.
[src:ldo-regulator/dropout-voltage] The output voltage can only be held constant within specified limits.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] A **low-dropout regulator** (**LDO regulator**) is a type of a DC linear voltage regulator circuit that can operate even when the supply voltage is very close to the output voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The disadvantage is that linear DC regulators must dissipate heat in order to operate.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The adjustable low-dropout regulator debuted on April 12, 1977 in an *Electronic Design* article entitled "*Break Loose from Fixed IC Regulators*".
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The article was written by Robert Dobkin, an IC designer then working for National Semiconductor.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Because of this, National Semiconductor claims the title of "*LDO inventor*".
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Dobkin later left National Semiconductor in 1981 and founded Linear Technology where he was the chief technology officer.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The main components are a power FET and a differential amplifier (error amplifier).
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] One input of the differential amplifier monitors the fraction of the output determined by the resistor ratio of R1 and R2.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The second input to the differential amplifier is from a stable voltage reference (bandgap reference).
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] If the output voltage rises too high relative to the reference voltage, the drive to the power FET changes to maintain a constant output voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Low-dropout (LDO) regulators operate similarly to all linear voltage regulators.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The main difference between LDO and non-LDO regulators is their schematic topology.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Instead of an emitter follower topology, low-dropout regulators consist of an open collector or open drain topology, where the transistor may be easily driven into saturation with the voltages available to the regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] This allows the voltage drop from the unregulated voltage to the regulated voltage to be as low as the saturation voltage across the transistor.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] When this voltage is less than Vref, the opamp will turn on the pass element.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] If a bipolar transistor is used, as opposed to a field-effect transistor or JFET, significant additional power may be lost to control it, whereas non-LDO regulators take that power from voltage drop itself.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] For high voltages under very low Vin-Vout difference there will be significant power loss in the control circuit.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Because the power control element is an inverter, another inverting amplifier is required to control it, increasing circuit complexity compared to simple linear regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Power FETs may be preferable in order to reduce power consumption, yet this poses problems when the regulator is used for low input voltage, since FETs usually require 5 to 10 V to close completely.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] where $I_{\text{Q}}$ is the quiescent current required by the LDO for its internal circuitry.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] However, when the LDO is in full operation (i.e., supplying current to the load) generally: $I_{\text{OUT}}\gg I_{\text{Q}}$ .
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] It is important to keep thermal considerations in mind when using a low drop-out linear regulator.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Having high current and/or a wide differential between input and output voltage could lead to large power dissipation.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Additionally, efficiency will suffer as the differential widens.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Depending on the package, excessive power dissipation could damage the LDO or cause it to go into thermal shutdown.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Quiescent current is current drawn by the LDO in order to control its internal circuitry for proper operation.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The series pass element, topologies, and ambient temperature are the primary contributors to quiescent current.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Many applications do not require an LDO to be in full operation all of the time (i.e. supplying current to the load).
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] In this idle state the LDO still draws a small amount of quiescent current in order to keep the internal circuitry ready in case a load is presented.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] In addition to regulating voltage, LDOs can also be used as filters.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] This is especially useful when a system is using switchers, which introduce a ripple in the output voltage occurring at the switching frequency.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Left alone, this ripple has the potential to adversely affect the performance of oscillators, data converters, and RF systems being powered by the switcher.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] However, any power source, not just switchers, can contain AC elements that may be undesirable for design.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Two specifications that should be considered when using an LDO as a filter are power supply rejection ratio (PSRR) and output noise.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Speed is indicated by the rise time of the current at the output as it varies from 0 mA load current (no load) to the maximum load current.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] This is basically decided by the bandwidth of the error amplifier.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] It is also expected from an LDO to provide a quiet and stable output in all circumstances (example of possible perturbation could be: sudden change of the input voltage or output current).
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Stability analysis put in place some performance metrics to get such a behaviour and involve placing poles and zeros appropriately.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Most of the time, there is a dominant pole that arise at low frequencies while other poles and zeros are pushed at high frequencies.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] PSRR refers to the LDO's ability to reject ripple it sees at its input.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] As part of its regulation, the error amplifier and bandgap reference attenuate any spikes in the input voltage that deviate from the internal reference to which it is compared.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] In an ideal LDO, the output voltage would be solely composed of the DC frequency.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] However, the error amplifier is limited in its ability to gain small spikes at high frequencies.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] As an example, an LDO that has a PSRR of 55 dB at 1 MHz attenuates a 1 mV input ripple at this frequency to just 1.78 μV at the output.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] A 6 dB increase in PSRR roughly equates to an increase in attenuation by a factor of 2.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Most LDOs have relatively high PSRR at lower frequencies (10 Hz – 1 kHz).
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] However, a Performance LDO is distinguished in having high PSRR over a broad frequency spectrum (10 Hz – 5 MHz).
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Having high PSRR over a wide band allows the LDO to reject high-frequency noise like that arising from a switcher.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Similar to other specifications, PSRR fluctuates over frequency, temperature, current, output voltage, and the voltage differential.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The noise from the LDO itself must also be considered in filter design.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Like other electronic devices, LDOs are affected by thermal noise, bipolar shot noise, and flicker noise.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Each of these phenomena contributes noise to the output voltage, mostly concentrated over the lower end of the frequency spectrum.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] In order to properly filter AC frequencies, an LDO must both reject ripple at the input while introducing minimal noise at the output.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Efforts to attenuate ripple from the input voltage could be in vain if a noisy LDO just adds that noise back again at the output.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Load regulation is a measure of the circuit's ability to maintain the specified output voltage under varying load conditions.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The worst case of the output voltage variations occurs as the load current transitions from zero to its maximum rated value or vice versa.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Line regulation is a measure of the circuit's ability to maintain the specified output voltage with varying input voltage.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Like load regulation, line regulation is a steady state parameter—all frequency components are neglected.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Increasing DC open-loop current gain improves the line regulation.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The transient response is the maximum allowable output voltage variation for a load current step change.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] Where ${\textstyle \Delta t_{1}}$ corresponds to the closed-loop bandwidth of an LDO regulator. ${\textstyle \Delta V_{\text{ESR}}}$ is the voltage variation resulting from the presence of the ESR ( ${\textstyle R_{\text{ESR}}}$ ) of the output capacitor.
[src:ldo-regulator/low-dropout-regulator] The application determines how low this value should be.
